But Jerome lays no claim to origin- ality, or rather he repudiates the claim at the very outset of his commentasy on the Galatiam. His work is a digest of his vast reading, principally based, as he tells us, on the labours of Origen. The whole is doubtless moulded and coloured by his own genius, and is thus placed above the level of a mere compilation.
